"""
MKT Context — Luke all 24 chapters
Output: data/commentary/mkt-context/luke.json
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DATA = {
  "1": {
    "1": '<p>Luke-Acts is a two-volume work addressed to Theophilus (a Greek name meaning friend of God or beloved of God), probably a Roman Gentile patron of high standing (the title most excellent / kratiste is used for Roman officials, cf. Acts 23:26, 24:3). The prologue (1:1-4) follows the conventions of Hellenistic historical writing, establishing Luke as a careful researcher who investigated the traditions. The Gospel was written ca. 80-90 CE, after Mark (which Luke uses as a source) but before the Pastorals assume a settled Pauline legacy. Luke-Acts together constitute the longest contribution by a single author to the NT canon.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The opening chapters of Luke (1-2) are saturated with Semitic style (Hebraisms, parallelisms, Greek that translates Hebrew idioms), suggesting Luke is either using Hebrew/Aramaic sources or deliberately writing in a Septuagint style to evoke the OT narrative. Zechariah is introduced as a Levitical priest of the division of Abijah — one of the 24 priestly divisions established by David (1 Chr 24:10). Each division served two one-week periods per year; the incense offering was assigned by lot among the many priests of each division, making it a once-in-a-lifetime honor. The setting of the angel\'s appearance at the altar of incense (the holy place, just outside the holy of holies) is the spatial marker of the narrative\'s sacred beginning.</p>'
  },
  "2": {
    "1": '<p>The census of Caesar Augustus (63 BCE - 14 CE) raises the most discussed historical question in Luke\'s infancy narrative. Luke places the birth during a worldwide census while Quirinius was governing Syria (v.2). The known Quirinius census occurred in 6-7 CE, which conflicts with the Herodian birth-dating (Herod died 4 BCE). Scholars have proposed that an earlier census or registration during an earlier Quirinius governorship may explain the discrepancy; others read prote as before (before Quirinius was governor); others identify a scribal error. Whatever the resolution, Luke\'s historical-anchoring intention is clear: the birth of Jesus is embedded in universal history (Caesar Augustus, the Roman census system), not merely in Jewish sacred time.</p>',
    "41": '<p>The Passover pilgrimage to Jerusalem was required of all Jewish adult males who lived within 15 miles of Jerusalem (m. Hagigah 1:1), though by the first century many diaspora Jews and pious Galileans made the pilgrimage annually. The family caravan from Galilee to Jerusalem took approximately 4-5 days on foot. The social structure of the pilgrimage is key to understanding the story of the lost boy (v.43): extended families and neighbors traveled together in large groups; it was natural to assume a child was with relatives in the caravan before noticing his absence at nightfall. The three-day search (journey back one day, search one day, find on the third day) has been noticed as a resurrection-echo in Luke\'s typological pattern.</p>'
  },
  "3": {
    "1": '<p>Luke\'s sixfold dating of John\'s ministry (v.1-2) is the most precisely anchored historical introduction in the Gospels: the 15th year of Tiberius Caesar (28-29 CE by most reckonings, possibly 26 CE if counted from Tiberius\'s co-regency), with Pilate as Judean prefect (26-36 CE), Herod Antipas as Galilean tetrarch (4 BCE - 39 CE), Philip as Iturean tetrarch (4 BCE - 34 CE), Lysanias as Abilene tetrarch (dates uncertain), and Annas and Caiaphas as high priests (Annas served 6-15 CE; Caiaphas 18-36 CE). Luke\'s secular-historical anchoring reflects his apologetic purpose: Christianity is a public, datable, geographically specific event, not a mystery cult with hidden origins.</p>'
  },
  "4": {
    "16": '<p>The Nazareth synagogue scene is both Luke\'s inauguration narrative and his programmatic Christological-social summary. Synagogue worship in the first century included Torah readings, Prophets readings (<em>haftarah</em>), prayer, and exposition; there was no fixed lectionary for the Prophets readings, allowing Jesus to select Isa 61:1-2. The Jubilee language of Isa 61 (release to captives, year of the Lord\'s favor = the year of Jubilee from Lev 25) would have evoked economic liberation for the impoverished Galilean audience. The crowd\'s initial favorable response (v.22) followed by fury (v.28) when Jesus cites the Gentile precedents (Zarephath, Naaman) is the reception pattern that the whole Gospel will repeat: initial receptivity followed by rejection at the universal-mission implication.</p>'
  },
  "6": {
    "20": '<p>The Sermon on the Plain (6:17-49) is Luke\'s parallel to Matthew\'s Sermon on the Mount — shorter, more economically concrete, and delivered at a level place (v.17) rather than a mountain. The four beatitudes and four woes reflect the Jubilee-reversal theology of Isa 61: the poor are blessed (and the rich are denounced), the hungry are satisfied (and the full are left empty), the mourners are comforted (and those who laugh are warned). Luke\'s social emphasis (actual poverty, actual hunger) alongside Matthew\'s more spiritualized version (poor in spirit, hunger for righteousness) reflects different community contexts: Luke\'s mixed Gentile-Jewish audience includes the economically marginalized; Matthew\'s Jewish-Christian community reads poverty through the anawim tradition.</p>'
  },
  "7": {
    "1": '<p>The healing of the centurion\'s servant (7:1-10) appears in both Luke and Matthew (8:5-13), with Luke adding details that reflect a Gentile patron-client relationship: the centurion sends Jewish elders first (respected intermediaries) and then friends (personal representatives), never approaching Jesus directly. This distance-protocol reflects Mediterranean honor-shame culture: the centurion recognizes that direct approach would obligate Jesus and risk social boundary-violation. His own statement (I am not worthy for you to come under my roof) is a precise formulation of the patron-client inequality. Jesus\'s wonder at his faith (v.9) — the only time in the Synoptics Jesus marvels at faith — singles out the Gentile as the paradigm believer.</p>'
  },
  "10": {
    "25": '<p>The parable of the Good Samaritan (10:25-37) is Luke\'s unique contribution to the NT. The lawyer\'s question (who is my neighbor?) is a genuine Second Temple debate: some interpretations limited neighbor to fellow Jews or even only to Pharisees; others extended it to proselytes. The Samaritan as hero is the most provocative element: Samaritans and Jews had long-standing mutual hostility (John 4:9, Josephus Ant. 18.30 describes violent incidents). The parable does not define who counts as a neighbor (the expected answer) but asks which of the three acted as a neighbor — shifting the question from classification (who is in my neighbor-category?) to disposition (how do I neighbor?). The priest and Levite\'s failure is probably a purity concern: contact with a potentially dead body would render them unclean for temple service.</p>'
  },
  "15": {
    "1": '<p>The three parables of Luke 15 (lost sheep, lost coin, lost son) are unique to Luke and form a unified trilogy on the divine initiative in seeking and finding the lost. The social context of v.1-2 is critical: the Pharisees and scribes murmur because Jesus receives (accepts, welcomes, eats with) sinners. Table fellowship was a community boundary marker in first-century Judaism: with whom you ate defined who you included. The parable trilogy is Jesus\'s theological defense of his boundary-transgressing practice: God himself seeks the lost (lost sheep, lost coin) and runs to embrace the returning prodigal — therefore the community formed around this God should reflect the same excess of seeking, welcoming love.</p>'
  },
  "16": {
    "19": '<p>The parable of the Rich Man and Lazarus (16:19-31) is Luke\'s unique social-reversal parable with an afterlife scene. The rich man\'s clothing (purple and fine linen) are the markers of extreme wealth in antiquity (purple dye was extraordinarily expensive; fine linen was the priestly and royal cloth). Lazarus (the only named character in a Jesus parable) is a name meaning God has helped — the divine help he received was absent in life but present in death. The parable concludes with the theological point that Abraham\'s bosom (the Jewish term for the blessed state of the righteous after death) is not available to those who ignore the Law and the Prophets (v.29,31) — reinforcing Luke\'s consistent theme of wealth as a spiritual danger.</p>'
  },
  "19": {
    "1": '<p>Jericho (19:1-10, Zacchaeus) is the last stop before Jerusalem on the road up from the Jordan Valley. Zacchaeus as chief tax collector (architelones) — a title not found elsewhere in the NT — suggests he was the head contractor for the Jericho district, which would have been profitable: Jericho was a wealthy oasis city with balsam groves, a major product of the region. His height problem and the sycamore tree (ficus sycomorus, a low-branching tree common in the Jordan Valley) are vivid geographic details. Zacchaeus\'s offer of fourfold restitution and 50% distribution to the poor exceeds what repentance required: the Mosaic law required 20% addition (Lev 6:5, Num 5:7) and fourfold only for stolen animals (Exod 22:1).</p>'
  },
  "22": {
    "3": '<p>The Last Supper\'s Passover context (22:7-13) is thoroughly Lukan: Luke adds the preparatory detail (Peter and John sent to find the room), the eschatological-earnest longing (I have earnestly desired to eat this Passover with you, v.15), and the unique covenant-cup sequence (some manuscripts give two cups in Luke — a feature that may reflect the four Passover cups). The argument about greatness at the table (vv.24-27, unique to Luke) is placed immediately after the institution, as if the disciples misunderstand the service-Christology just enacted. Luke\'s passion narrative contains significant unique material: the Agony (v.43-44, in some manuscripts), the arrest crowd with clubs and swords, and the healing of the high priest\'s servant\'s ear (v.51).</p>'
  },
  "23": {
    "1": '<p>Luke\'s passion narrative adds several unique elements that serve his apologetic purpose: Pilate\'s triple declaration of Jesus\'s innocence (23:4, 14, 22 — I find no guilt in this man), the Herod Antipas episode (23:7-12, unique to Luke), the mourning daughters of Jerusalem (23:27-31), the repentant criminal (23:39-43), and the Lukan last word (23:46, quoting Ps 31:5). The triple Pilate-innocence formula is Luke\'s most explicit apologetic point: the Roman governor found Jesus not guilty, therefore Roman law and Roman Christians need not regard Jesus as a criminal. The political authorities\' guilt lies in capitulation to Jewish pressure, not in their own judgment.</p>'
  },
  "24": {
    "13": '<p>The Emmaus road appearance (24:13-35) is Luke\'s unique and most extended resurrection narrative. Emmaus has been tentatively identified with modern Motza or Abu Ghosh, approximately 11 km from Jerusalem. The disciples\' unrecognized conversation with the risen Jesus (the recognition-delayed pattern echoes Gen 42:7-8, Joseph unrecognized by his brothers) culminates in the breaking of bread — the Eucharistic gesture that opens their eyes. Luke\'s narrative implies that the Lord\'s Supper is one of the primary contexts for recognition of the risen Christ; the post-Easter community encounters the risen one in the sharing of bread, as in the Upper Room. The Emmaus account grounds the Eucharistic practice of the early church in a resurrection-recognition event.</p>'
  }
}

# Gap-fill ch 14 — all 35 verses
FILL_CH14 = {
  "14": {
    "1": "<p>The third Pharisee dinner invitation (cf. 7:36; 11:37; 14:1) continues Luke&#8217;s pattern of Jesus eating with Pharisees while teaching and healing. &#8220;Being carefully watched&#8221; (<em>autoi &#275;san paraterumenoi auton</em>) uses the same legal-observation verb as 6:7 &#8212; the Pharisees are constituting themselves as witnesses for a potential Sabbath-violation charge. The dinner setting makes the social stakes high: the host&#8217;s reputation is bound up in the success of the meal and the behavior of all who recline at his table.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&#8220;Abnormal swelling of his body&#8221; (<em>hydr&#333;pikos</em>, dropsy/edema) &#8212; pathological fluid retention, often a symptom of heart or kidney failure; Luke the physician uses the medical term precisely. The man&#8217;s presence at a Pharisee&#8217;s Sabbath dinner is unusual &#8212; some interpreters suggest he was planted as a test; others that his social connections brought him there. Either way, Jesus is being presented with a visible need and a watching audience of legal experts.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Jesus initiates the legal question himself rather than healing first: &#8220;Is it lawful to heal on the Sabbath or not?&#8221; &#8212; reversing the dynamic of 6:7 where the Pharisees were watching for him to act. By posing the halakhic question publicly before acting, Jesus forces his opponents to take a position. Their silence is legally significant: they cannot say no (they cannot definitively ban healing by speech-act without rejecting the <em>piku&#7745;ach nefesh</em> principle) and will not say yes (because that validates his action).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The silence of the Pharisees and lawyers is effectively tacit legal assent: by not answering they cannot later make a charge of Sabbath violation without exposing their own inconsistency. &#8220;Taking hold of the man&#8221; (<em>epilabomenos</em>) &#8212; physical contact healing; touching the afflicted person was not itself prohibited on Sabbath (unlike the mixing of medications or the application of poultices, which were debated). Jesus heals by word and touch, sends the man away, and then makes the argument of v.5.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&#8220;If one of you has a child or an ox that falls into a well on the Sabbath&#8221; &#8212; the child-or-ox-in-the-pit argument from the lighter-to-the-weightier (Heb. <em>qal wahomer</em>). The Damascus Document (CD 11:13&#8211;14) forbids pulling a living animal out on the Sabbath even with a ladder; this was the Essene strict position. Mainstream Pharisaic halakhah permitted it. Jesus uses the Pharisaic position against any residual strictness: if you rescue an animal or child on Sabbath, how much more should you heal a human being?</p>",
    "6": "<p>Second time in Luke where Jesus&#8217;s Sabbath halakhic argument leaves the opponents without a reply (cf. 6:9). The pattern of unanswerable argument followed by healing followed by silence appears three times in the Sabbath controversies (6:6&#8211;11; 13:10&#8211;17; 14:1&#8211;6). The silence of legal experts is not mere embarrassment but a narrative signal: the Jesus-school&#8217;s interpretation of Sabbath law cannot be refuted within the terms of the debate.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The parable of seat-taking at a wedding feast is prompted by direct observation of social behavior: Jesus notices guests picking the places of honour (<em>tas pr&#333;toklisias</em>, the first-reclining places). Seating at a formal banquet was arranged by social rank, and the most honoured position was the closest to the host. The social anxiety about where to sit &#8212; risking humiliation by claiming too high a seat, or losing social standing by sitting too low &#8212; was a recognized feature of elite-dinner culture in the Greco-Roman world.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Proverbs 25:6&#8211;7 is the OT background: &#8220;Do not exalt yourself in the king&#8217;s presence, and do not claim a place among his great men; it is better for him to say to you, &#8216;Come up here,&#8217; than for him to humiliate you before his nobles.&#8221; Jesus is not simply giving social-climbing advice but using the wisdom tradition&#8217;s social observation as the vehicle for an eschatological principle. The wedding feast (<em>gamon</em>) setting introduces the banquet-as-kingdom-symbol that will carry through to v.15&#8211;24.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The public humiliation of displacement &#8212; &#8220;give this person your seat&#8221; &#8212; was a serious event in the Mediterranean honor-shame social world. Being moved from a high seat to a lower one in front of the assembled guests was a public declaration that your self-assessment of your own honor was wrong. The &#8220;shame&#8221; (<em>aischyn&#275;</em>) of v.9 is the formal, public loss of honor that results from the exposed presumption. The social mechanics make the eschatological point: presumptuous self-exaltation invites divine correction.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&#8220;Friend, move up higher&#8221; (<em>prosanab&#275;thi an&#333;teron</em>) &#8212; the public honoring of the person who took the lowest place is the reverse scenario. &#8220;Glory before all who sit at the table&#8221; (<em>doxa en&#333;pion pant&#333;n t&#333;n synanakeimenōn soi</em>) &#8212; the honor is explicitly public and witnessed. The honor-shame dynamic is fully engaged: to receive an invitation to move up is to have one&#8217;s social standing confirmed and elevated before witnesses. The scene maps exactly onto the Magnificat&#8217;s &#8220;he has brought down the powerful from their thrones and lifted up the humble&#8221; (1:52).</p>",
    "11": "<p>&#8220;All those who exalt themselves will be humbled, and those who humble themselves will be exalted&#8221; &#8212; the eschatological principle stated in maxim form; the maxim recurs at 18:14 after the Pharisee-and-Tax-Collector parable. OT background: Isa 2:17 (&#8220;the arrogance of man will be brought low and human pride humbled&#8221;), Prov 3:34 (&#8220;he mocks proud mockers but shows favor to the humble&#8221;, quoted in Jas 4:6 and 1 Pet 5:5). In Luke the principle applies both to social behavior (dinner table) and to eschatological status (who enters the kingdom).</p>",
    "12": "<p>The host instruction is the positive application of the reversal principle: &#8220;do not invite your friends, brothers, relatives, or rich neighbors&#8221; &#8212; those who can reciprocate. The patronage-reciprocity system operated on exactly this principle: feasting with equals created mutual obligations of return-feasting. Seneca (<em>De Beneficiis</em> 2.17) discusses the social obligation of reciprocity; the Greco-Roman dinner party was a carefully managed exchange of honor and obligation. Jesus&#8217;s instruction removes the economic rationality from the invitation.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&#8220;Invite the poor, the crippled, the lame, the blind&#8221; &#8212; the fourfold list recurs in v.21 (the banquet parable) and echoes Isa 35:5&#8211;6 (messianic restoration: the blind, deaf, lame, and mute are healed). These are the same categories excluded from temple service (Lev 21:18) and from the Qumran community (1QSa 2:3&#8211;10 excluded the physically impaired from the messianic assembly). Jesus&#8217;s instruction inverts both temple and Qumran practice: the excluded ones are explicitly invited.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&#8220;You will be repaid at the resurrection of the righteous&#8221; (<em>anastasis t&#333;n dikai&#333;n</em>) &#8212; the Pharisaic doctrine of the resurrection of the righteous (debated with the Sadducees, who denied resurrection; cf. Acts 23:6&#8211;8) is invoked as the eschatological mechanism for recompense. The host who gives without possibility of human reciprocation will be repaid by God at the resurrection. This also implicitly endorses the Pharisaic position on resurrection against the Sadducees, while pointing the doctrine&#8217;s practical application in a direction the Pharisees themselves may not have expected.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&#8220;Blessed is the one who will eat at the feast in the kingdom of God&#8221; &#8212; the exclamatory beatitude from a dinner guest echoes the messianic banquet expectations of Isa 25:6&#8211;9 (&#8220;On this mountain the LORD Almighty will prepare a feast of rich food for all peoples&#8221;). &#8220;Eat bread in the kingdom of God&#8221; was a recognized Second Temple idiom for eschatological salvation; 1 En. 62:14 describes the righteous eating with the Son of Man; 2 Bar. 29:4 describes the messianic era as a time of abundant food. The dinner guest&#8217;s beatitude is pious but also naive &#8212; assuming his own inclusion.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The Great Banquet parable responds to the naive beatitude by showing that invited guests may not attend. The host is unidentified but the parable&#8217;s context (a Pharisee&#8217;s dinner, discussion of kingdom invitation) makes the theological mapping clear: God is the host, the invitation is the gospel, and the invited guests&#8217; refusal is the subject of the parable. The &#8220;many guests&#8221; (<em>pollous</em>) had already been invited &#8212; the first invitation (corresponding to the OT&#8217;s prophetic summons to Israel) has already been accepted in principle.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The two-stage invitation system &#8212; a prior invitation followed by the servant&#8217;s summons when the feast is ready &#8212; was the custom of first-century elite dining: guests were invited in advance and then summoned when the meal was actually prepared. Evidence from ancient letters and narrative sources (Esth 5:8; 6:14) confirms the practice. The second summons is the one reported here; the refusals at this stage are doubly offensive because the guests had already committed to attend when first invited.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The first excuse (field purchase) &#8212; &#8220;I must go and see it&#8221; &#8212; is transparently implausible: a careful buyer inspects and negotiates before purchasing, not after. The implausibility signals that this is an excuse, not a genuine conflict. In Palestinian agrarian society, land was the primary form of wealth; investing in land was the most socially valued economic activity. The &#8220;please excuse me&#8221; (<em>er&#333;t&#333; se, eche me parēt&#275;menon</em>) is a polite formula that does not conceal the refusal.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The second excuse (five yoke of oxen to test) &#8212; similarly implausible: you test a team of oxen before purchasing, not after. Five yoke of oxen (ten animals) represents substantial agricultural wealth; a peasant farmer would own at most one pair. The conspicuous wealth of the excuses &#8212; purchased field, five yoke of oxen, newly married &#8212; signals that the declining guests are the comfortable, landed, and domestically settled &#8212; those who have found their security in this-world goods.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&#8220;I have just got married, so I can&#8217;t come&#8221; (<em>gynaika egēma kai dia touto ou dynamai elthein</em>) &#8212; the Torah exemption from military service for newlyweds (Deut 20:7; 24:5) was recognized in rabbinic tradition but applied to warfare, not social invitations. The bluntness of &#8220;I cannot come&#8221; (no &#8220;please excuse me&#8221;) makes this the most direct refusal. The three excuses together cover the three categories of Deut 20:5&#8211;7 (new house, new vineyard, new wife) &#8212; suggesting a deliberate echo of the Deuteronomic military exemptions reapplied to the kingdom invitation.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The host&#8217;s anger (<em>&#333;rgisth&#275; ho oikodespot&#275;s</em>) &#8212; in the Mediterranean honor-shame world, the invitees&#8217; last-minute refusals were public insults to the host&#8217;s honor; the anger is proportionate. The replacement guest list (poor, crippled, blind, lame) is identical to v.13 &#8212; the eschatological inclusion of those the social system excludes. &#8220;Streets and alleys of the town&#8221; (<em>plateias kai rhymas t&#275;s pole&#333;s</em>) &#8212; the public thoroughfares where the marginalized spent their time; these are the day-laborers, beggars, and outcasts.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&#8220;There is still room&#8221; &#8212; the servant&#8217;s report that the first replacement wave has not filled the hall triggers the second expansion of the invitation. The abundance of the feast exceeds the capacity of the original guest list, the street population, and now extends to the roads and lanes outside the city. The image of an inexhaustibly generous host whose table has no limit echoes Isa 55:1&#8211;2 (&#8220;Come, all you who are thirsty&#8230; come, buy and eat! Come, buy wine and milk without money and without cost&#8221;).</p>",
    "23": "<p>&#8220;The roads and country lanes&#8221; (<em>hodous kai phragmous</em>) &#8212; the expansion beyond the city walls to the countryside, where travelers and the rural poor would be found; &#8220;compel them to come in&#8221; (<em>anankason eiselthein</em>) &#8212; urgent, insistent persuasion of those who would be reluctant (the poor and rural outsider would be hesitant to enter a great feast uninvited). Augustine&#8217;s later use of this phrase to justify coercive conversion is contextually unjustified; the compulsion is the host&#8217;s relentless generosity overcoming the guests&#8217; reluctance.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&#8220;Not one of those who were invited will get a taste of my banquet&#8221; &#8212; the final exclusion of the original invitees is the application to the Pharisees at the dinner table: those who consider themselves the natural heirs of the kingdom invitation and decline to enter through the narrow door (13:24&#8211;25) will find their place taken by Gentiles and sinners. Luke&#8217;s parable has a clear salvation-historical application: Israel&#8217;s leadership declining the messianic invitation, and the Gentiles taking their place (Acts 13:46; 28:28).</p>",
    "25": "<p>The shift from the Pharisee&#8217;s dinner table to the road reflects the journey structure of Luke 9:51&#8211;19:44: Jesus is traveling to Jerusalem with large Passover pilgrim crowds. The &#8220;large crowds traveling with him&#8221; (<em>syneporeuonto de aut&#333; ochloi polloi</em>) are potential disciples who need to understand the cost of the journey they are undertaking. The discipleship teachings of vv.25&#8211;35 are addressed to these crowds rather than to the inner disciple group.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&#8220;Hate father and mother, wife and children, brothers and sisters&#8221; &#8212; the Semitic comparative use of &#8220;hate&#8221; (<em>mise&#333;</em>) as &#8220;love less&#8221; is well established: Gen 29:30&#8211;31 uses &#8220;Leah was hated&#8221; as a synonym for &#8220;loved less than Rachel.&#8221; Matt 10:37 gives the non-hyperbolic version: &#8220;loves father or mother more than me is not worthy of me.&#8221; The social cost is nonetheless real: the itinerant missionary lifestyle required abandoning the primary social obligations of the Mediterranean family structure.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The cross-bearing command (second time, cf. 9:23) is placed in the Jerusalem-journey context where crucifixion as a Roman execution method was visible reality. The Passover pilgrimage road would have included vivid memories of Roman punitive crucifixions in Galilee (Josephus records multiple mass crucifixions in the first-century Jewish-Roman context). Jesus&#8217;s audience heard this not as metaphor but as the literal description of a condemned man&#8217;s walk to execution.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The tower-building calculation parable &#8212; the agricultural watchtower (<em>pyrgos</em>) was a standard feature of Palestinian hillside vineyards; Isa 5:2 and Mark 12:1 both mention towers in vineyard descriptions; the Lachish reliefs show Israelite tower-building. The cost calculation (<em>psēphizei t&#275;n dapan&#275;n</em>, counts the expense) before laying a foundation is the practical wisdom that the parable uses to frame the discipleship decision. Enthusiasm without calculation leads to half-finished projects and public ridicule.</p>",
    "29": "<p>&#8220;Everyone who sees it will ridicule him&#8221; (<em>pairetin empaizein aut&#333;</em>) &#8212; the incomplete tower was visible from the road and would become the subject of village mockery for years. In a small agrarian community where everyone knew everyone&#8217;s projects and resources, the abandoned foundation was a permanent monument to failed judgment. The social shame of public ridicule was one of the most powerful motivators in the Mediterranean world &#8212; here enlisted as an argument for realistic self-assessment before commitment.</p>",
    "30": "<p>&#8220;This person began to build and wasn&#8217;t able to finish&#8221; &#8212; the mockery formula; the two parables (tower, king-going-to-war) frame the discipleship decision as a rational-calculus question: do not commit unless you can sustain the commitment. The repeated &#8220;cannot be my disciple&#8221; (<em>ou dynatai einai mou math&#275;t&#275;s</em>) in vv.26, 27, and 33 creates the emphasis: this is a three-times-stated qualification, not an enthusiastic invitation.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The king-going-to-war calculation &#8212; a small king (ten thousand troops) deciding whether to engage a larger king (twenty thousand) must first &#8220;consider&#8221; (<em>bouleusetai</em>, deliberate/counsel) whether the engagement is winnable. The disproportion (10,000 vs. 20,000) makes the calculation stark. The king&#8217;s primary alternative to war is peace terms; similarly, the disciple&#8217;s alternative to full commitment to Jesus is no commitment &#8212; half-commitment is precisely the unstable position the parable warns against.</p>",
    "32": "<p>&#8220;Terms of peace&#8221; (<em>er&#333;t&#257; ta pros eir&#275;n&#275;n</em>) &#8212; the diplomatic formula for negotiated surrender before battle; in the Greek world, sending a delegation (<em>presbeian</em>) was the recognized alternative to combat. The parable does not prescribe withdrawal from discipleship but asks for honest assessment. The Lukan application: better to honestly assess the cost and not follow than to begin following enthusiastically and abandon the commitment when the cross-bearing becomes concrete.</p>",
    "33": "<p>&#8220;Those of you who do not give up everything you have cannot be my disciples&#8221; &#8212; the conclusion states the cost explicitly: total relinquishment. <em>Apotassetai</em> (give up, renounce, say farewell to) echoes the farewell-to-family of 9:61; it is the no-looking-back gesture of total commitment. Luke&#8217;s distinctive emphasis on the economic dimension of discipleship (5:11,28; 18:22; 19:8) makes this not merely spiritual detachment but actual economic reorientation around the community of the kingdom.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The salt saying &#8212; salt was the essential preservation and seasoning agent in the ancient world; Roman soldiers received a salt allowance (<em>salarium</em>, giving us &#8220;salary&#8221;). The theoretical impossibility of pure NaCl losing saltiness (it doesn&#8217;t) is overcome by the practical reality of impure rock salt from the Dead Sea region: when the sodium chloride leaches out, the remaining calcium sulfate looks like salt but has no salt-properties. The saying applies to disciples who have the appearance but not the substance of committed following.</p>",
    "35": "<p>&#8220;Thrown out&#8221; (<em>exō ballousin auto</em>) &#8212; salt that has lost its properties cannot be used even as fertilizer (unlike wood ash) or as a manure-pile additive; it is useless and discarded. The &#8220;ears to hear, let them hear&#8221; formula (<em>ho ech&#333;n &#333;ta akouein akouet&#333;</em>) marks the saying as a wisdom-teaching requiring interpretive effort (cf. 8:8; Matt 11:15; 13:9,43); the disciples must discern which aspect of their commitment is the &#8220;salt&#8221; that must not be lost.</p>"
  }
}

# Gap-fill ch 15 — 31 verses (v.1 already in DATA)
FILL_CH15 = {
  "15": {
    "2": "<p>&#8220;This man welcomes sinners and eats with them&#8221; (<em>prosdechetai hamartōlous kai synesthiei autois</em>) &#8212; the Pharisees&#8217; complaint is not merely moral but social and theological: eating with someone was a declaration of community inclusion. In Second Temple Judaism, table fellowship was a community boundary marker; sharing a meal communicated shared purity status and social solidarity. By eating with &#8220;sinners&#8221; (those who did not observe Pharisaic halakhah), Jesus is including them in his fellowship without requiring the repentance and restoration process the Pharisees considered necessary.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&#8220;He told them this parable&#8221; &#8212; the parable trilogy of ch. 15 is Jesus&#8217;s direct theological response to the Pharisees&#8217; complaint of v.2. The three parables function together as a threefold argument for the divine initiative in seeking and the appropriateness of celebrating the found. The progression (100 sheep, 10 coins, two sons) moves from the smallest to the most complex loss, and from the impersonal (sheep) to the personal (son).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The shepherd leaving the ninety-nine to search for the one lost sheep &#8212; the shepherd-flock imagery for God&#8217;s relationship to Israel pervades the OT: Ps 23, Ezek 34 (the extended critique of Israel&#8217;s bad shepherds and God&#8217;s promise to be the good shepherd), Isa 40:11. A flock of one hundred sheep is a modest but viable holding for a Galilean small farmer-shepherd. The leaving of the ninety-nine &#8220;in the open country&#8221; (<em>en t&#275; er&#275;m&#333;</em>) would have raised a mild objection: are the ninety-nine safe? But the parable focuses on the seeking, not the management of the majority.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&#8220;Joyfully puts it on his shoulders&#8221; &#8212; the Good Shepherd carrying the found sheep is one of the oldest images in Christian art, derived from this passage. Carrying a found animal was a practical necessity (a frightened or injured sheep would not walk reliably); it was also an act of personal commitment and care that went beyond simple retrieval. The &#8220;joyfully&#8221; (<em>chair&#333;n</em>) names the emotional register: the finding produces joy before any subsequent celebration.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&#8220;He calls his friends and neighbors together and says, Rejoice with me&#8221; &#8212; the community celebration is a deliberate social act: the loss and recovery of a sheep would be known throughout a small Palestinian village; the call to shared rejoicing turns private recovery into communal celebration. The &#8220;Rejoice with me&#8221; formula (<em>sygcharēt&#275; moi</em>) echoes the angelic announcement pattern (1:58: neighbors and relatives rejoiced with Elizabeth) and anticipates v.9 (same formula for the coin).</p>",
    "7": "<p>&#8220;More joy in heaven over one sinner who repents than over ninety-nine righteous persons who do not need to repent&#8221; &#8212; the divine preference for the found-and-returned over the maintained-and-stable; the &#8220;righteous who do not need to repent&#8221; is gently ironic (everyone needs repentance; but those content with their righteousness generate less divine celebration than the genuinely returning). The &#8220;heaven rejoicing&#8221; over repentance is expressed in rabbinic literature: b. Sanhedrin 99b describes divine joy over the returning sinner.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The lost coin parable &#8212; the woman&#8217;s ten silver drachmas; a drachma was roughly a day&#8217;s wage. Some interpreters identify the ten coins as a bride-price or dowry head-chain worn by married women in Palestinian custom (the <em>&#39;isah</em>), giving the loss a marriage-covenant significance. Whether or not this is the specific reference, the point is that the coin has sentimental or economic value disproportionate to its market worth. The lighting of a lamp, sweeping, and careful search (<em>epistat&#333;s</em>, diligently) are the practical steps of someone who takes the loss seriously.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The community celebration &#8212; &#8220;she calls her friends and neighbors together and says, Rejoice with me&#8221; &#8212; exact parallel to v.6 (shepherd&#8217;s celebration). The pattern of the two parables is structurally identical: loss → diligent search → finding → joy → community celebration → divine application. The identical structure reinforces the single theological point: God&#8217;s response to recovering the lost is celebratory joy that invites the whole community to share. The Pharisees&#8217; murmuring is the refusal to join this community celebration.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&#8220;Rejoicing in the presence of the angels of God&#8221; (<em>char&#257; ginetai en&#333;pion t&#333;n aggelōn tou theou</em>) &#8212; not the angels themselves rejoicing but God rejoicing before his angelic court; the formulation is a circumlocution for &#8220;God rejoices.&#8221; The divine throne room as the scene of celebration when a sinner returns is the eschatological reality that the earthly dinner-party celebration (Jesus eating with sinners) images. The Pharisees who murmur are refusing to participate in heaven&#8217;s joy.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&#8220;There was a man who had two sons&#8221; &#8212; the third and climactic parable of the trilogy; both sons are &#8220;lost&#8221; in different ways: the younger in a far country through rebellion, the elder in the father&#8217;s house through resentment. The two-sons structure echoes the two-son patterns of the OT: Cain and Abel, Ishmael and Isaac, Esau and Jacob, the sons of Jacob; in each case the expected primogeniture order is disrupted. The parable maps onto the situation of ch.15: the sinners (younger son) and the Pharisees (elder son) both in relation to the Father (God).</p>",
    "12": "<p>&#8220;Give me my share of the estate&#8221; &#8212; demanding inheritance while the father is still alive was possible in Jewish law (m. BB 8:7) and Sirach (33:20&#8211;24 warns fathers against giving control of their property during their lifetime). But culturally it was an aggressive and shaming act, practically equivalent to wishing the father dead. The father&#8217;s compliance without protest or negotiation is not legally coerced but is a striking voluntary act of love that the elder son will later resent.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&#8220;Squandered his wealth in wild living&#8221; (<em>asōt&#333;s</em>, wastefully, recklessly) &#8212; the word <em>as&#333;tos</em> (from <em>a-s&#333;z&#333;</em>, cannot be saved/preserved) describes the irreversible dissipation of resources. &#8220;A distant country&#8221; (<em>ch&#333;ran makran</em>) &#8212; geographically and culturally distant, presumably Gentile; in a Gentile country, Jewish religious and dietary obligations are practically impossible to maintain. The son&#8217;s departure is not just economic rebellion but the beginning of religious defilement.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&#8220;A severe famine in that whole country&#8221; &#8212; famine in the ancient Mediterranean was a regular occurrence tied to harvest failure and drought; the son&#8217;s vulnerability was compounded by being without family network in a foreign land. The shame-spiral accelerates: his &#8220;coming to need&#8221; (<em>hyster&#275;thenai</em>) is the technical term for lacking necessities. The severity of the need is measured by the pig-feeding job of v.15.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&#8220;Hired himself out to a citizen of that country who sent him to feed pigs&#8221; &#8212; working with pigs for a Gentile employer was the maximum ritual defilement for a Jew; pigs were unclean animals (Lev 11:7; Deut 14:8), and proximity to them was impure. The son has reached the nadir of both economic destitution and ritual impurity. The &#8220;citizen of that country&#8221; (<em>polit&#275;n t&#275;s ch&#333;ras ekein&#275;s</em>) is a Gentile; the son is now a client of a Gentile pagan in Gentile territory, tending unclean animals.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&#8220;Longed to fill his stomach with the pods that the pigs were eating&#8221; &#8212; the pods (<em>keration</em>) are carob beans (Ceratonia siliqua), the locust-bean tree&#8217;s fruit, which was cheap animal fodder. The son&#8217;s hunger has reached the point where he covets the food reserved for pigs. &#8220;No one gave him anything&#8221; (<em>oud&#279;is edidou aut&#333;</em>) &#8212; the social isolation is complete; he has no patron, no family, no community; the Gentile employer provides no welfare. The phrase echoes the rich man and Lazarus (16:21) where the dogs attend Lazarus but &#8220;no one gave him anything.&#8221;</p>",
    "17": "<p>&#8220;When he came to his senses&#8221; (<em>eis heauton elth&#333;n</em>, coming to himself) &#8212; the Greek idiom for returning to right mind; the son&#8217;s dissipation was a kind of self-alienation or self-abandonment, and his recovery begins with self-knowledge. &#8220;My father&#8217;s hired servants have food to spare&#8221; &#8212; the contrast between the father&#8217;s household abundance (even the lowest workers have surplus) and the son&#8217;s starvation in the far country; the argument is purely pragmatic at this stage: he is hungry and there is food at home.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The rehearsed speech &#8212; &#8220;Father, I have sinned against heaven and against you&#8221; &#8212; the dual sin-confession echoes Exod 10:16 (Pharaoh: &#8220;I have sinned against the LORD your God and against you&#8221;) and acknowledges both the vertical (against heaven = against God) and horizontal (against the father) dimensions of his wrong. The son&#8217;s formulation is theologically accurate: his rebellion against his father was simultaneously rebellion against the God who established the family covenant-structure.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&#8220;Make me like one of your hired servants&#8221; (<em>poiēson me h&#333;s hena t&#333;n misthion sou</em>) &#8212; the <em>misthios</em> (hired servant) had lower status than a <em>doulos</em> (household slave) because he had no permanent household relationship; he was a day-laborer, not a member of the household. The son&#8217;s self-humbling requests the lowest rung of the household structure &#8212; not restoration as a son but mere employment. His calculation is still pragmatic: he wants food and safety, not necessarily relationship.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&#8220;While he was still a long way off, his father saw him&#8212;was filled with compassion&#8212;ran to him&#8212;threw his arms around him&#8212;kissed him&#8221; &#8212; five rapid actions before any speech; the father&#8217;s response is preemptive, physical, and un-calculating. That the father &#8220;saw him while still a long way off&#8221; implies he had been watching, perhaps from the roof or the elevated gate. Running was socially undignified for a Palestinian patriarch (required gathering the robe, exposing the legs); the father&#8217;s run is a deliberate self-lowering for the sake of the returning son.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The son begins his rehearsed speech &#8212; &#8220;Father, I have sinned against heaven and against you. I am no longer worthy to be called your son&#8221; &#8212; but the &#8220;make me like one of your hired servants&#8221; request (from v.19) is never spoken; the father interrupts before it reaches the request. The father&#8217;s interruption prevents the son from completing the self-degradation that would make him a servant rather than a son; the restoration is given before it is asked for.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The three restoration gifts &#8212; the best robe (<em>st&#333;l&#275;n t&#275;n pr&#333;t&#275;n</em>), a ring, sandals &#8212; are three status-restoration symbols. The best robe: covering nakedness and shame, marking household membership (cf. the robe given to the returning Esau, Gen 27:27&#8211;28 is a stretch, but robes as status markers are pervasive in OT narrative). The signet ring (<em>daktylion</em>): authority and family identity (cf. the ring given to Joseph, Gen 41:42). The sandals: free persons wore sandals; slaves went barefoot (the same sandal distinction appears in John the Baptist&#8217;s saying about Jesus&#8217;s sandals, 3:16).</p>",
    "23": "<p>&#8220;Bring the fattened calf&#8221; (<em>ton moschon ton siteuton</em>) &#8212; the specially fattened animal reserved for major celebrations; a household that raised a calf specifically for a feast had been anticipating some occasion of exceptional rejoicing. The immediacy (&#8220;quick!&#8221; in v.22) and the fattened calf suggest that the father&#8217;s preparations for celebration had an anticipatory quality &#8212; as if the return had been awaited. The &#8220;feast and celebrate&#8221; (<em>phagontes euphranthōmen</em>) is the same verb used for the rich man&#8217;s daily luxury (16:19: <em>euphrainomenos kath&#8217; h&#275;meran</em>).</p>",
    "24": "<p>&#8220;This son of mine was dead and is alive again; he was lost and is found&#8221; &#8212; the resurrection-language applied to the return from the far country; the son was effectively dead (to the family, to his covenant community, to himself) and is now alive. The dead-and-alive, lost-and-found formula is the theological core of the trilogy: it explains why heaven rejoices (vv.7,10) and why the father must celebrate. Death reversed by resurrection requires celebration; to refuse to celebrate is to be indifferent to resurrection.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The elder son &#8220;in the field&#8221; &#8212; working while the celebration is happening; his distance from the house is spatial but also relational. The elder son&#8217;s presence in the field is appropriate (he is the dutiful, working son) but also positions him as an outsider to the house-celebration that is happening without his knowledge or consent. The overheard music and dancing (<em>symphōnias kai chorōn</em>) &#8212; the celebration is full-bodied, joyful, and audible from outside.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The elder son calls a servant to inquire &#8212; he does not enter the house to find out directly; his distance from the father is already visible. The servant&#8217;s report will be his first information about his brother&#8217;s return. The use of a servant as intermediary rather than approaching the father directly anticipates the elder son&#8217;s overall posture of distance &#8212; he relates to the household through its formal structures rather than through personal relationship with the father.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The servant&#8217;s report: &#8220;Your brother has come&#8230; your father has killed the fattened calf because he has him back safe and sound (<em>hygiainom</em>)&#8221; &#8212; the servant frames it as good news; the healthy return of the younger son is the cause of the celebration. The elder son&#8217;s response will reveal that he does not share the servant&#8217;s evaluation. The use of &#8220;your brother&#8221; by the servant (vs. the elder son&#8217;s later &#8220;this son of yours&#8221; in v.30) marks the contrast in relational framing.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&#8220;The older brother became angry and refused to go in&#8221; (<em>&#333;rgisth&#275; kai ouk &#275;thelen eiselthein</em>) &#8212; the anger parallels the host&#8217;s anger in the Great Banquet parable (v.21), but with the opposite target: the host&#8217;s anger is at the refusers; the elder son&#8217;s anger is at the welcoming. The refusal to enter the feast is the elder son&#8217;s counterpart to the younger son&#8217;s departure to the far country; both are forms of separation from the father. &#8220;His father went out and pleaded with him&#8221; (<em>par&#275;kalei auton</em>) &#8212; the father does for the elder son exactly what he did for the younger son: he comes out to meet him.</p>",
    "29": "<p>&#8220;All these years I&#8217;ve been slaving for you&#8221; (<em>tosauta et&#275; doule&#363;</em>) &#8212; the elder son describes his service as slavery (<em>douleo</em>), not sonship; he has related to the father through performance-obligation rather than love. &#8220;Never disobeyed your orders&#8221; &#8212; the obedience is real but its motivation is now revealed as contractual, not relational. &#8220;You never gave me even a young goat&#8221; &#8212; the contrast with the fattened calf; the elder son&#8217;s resentment reveals that he has been keeping score, calculating the return on his service.</p>",
    "30": "<p>&#8220;This son of yours&#8221; (<em>ho huios sou houtos</em>) &#8212; the elder son refuses to say &#8220;my brother&#8221;; he has disinherited him relationally while the father has reinstated him legally. The added accusation &#8220;with prostitutes&#8221; (<em>meta porn&#333;n</em>) is not in the original narrative (the parable only says &#8220;wild living&#8221; in v.13); the elder son&#8217;s hostile embellishment may be his assumption or his desire to make the case against the restoration as strong as possible.</p>",
    "31": "<p>&#8220;You are always with me, and everything I have is yours&#8221; &#8212; the father&#8217;s gentle correction identifies the elder son&#8217;s category error: he has had continuous access to the father and all the father&#8217;s resources, but has not experienced them as gift. He has lived as a servant &#8220;earning&#8221; what is already fully his by being. The contrast with the younger son is that the elder son&#8217;s lostness is interior &#8212; he is present in the house but absent from the father&#8217;s heart; the younger son was absent from the house but is now found in the father&#8217;s embrace.</p>",
    "32": "<p>&#8220;We had to celebrate and be glad, because this brother of yours was dead and is alive again; he was lost and is found&#8221; &#8212; the father corrects the elder son&#8217;s language (&#8220;this brother of yours,&#8221; restoring the kinship the elder son severed) and repeats the dead-and-alive, lost-and-found formula of v.24. The &#8220;had to&#8221; (<em>edei</em>) is the necessity language used for the passion (9:22); the celebration of the resurrection-return is a divine necessity. The parable ends without reporting the elder son&#8217;s response &#8212; an open ending that invites the Pharisees (the story&#8217;s auditors) to decide whether they will enter the feast.</p>"
  }
}

# Gap-fill ch 16 — 30 verses (v.19 already in DATA)
FILL_CH16 = {
  "16": {
    "1": "<p>The Dishonest Manager parable (16:1&#8211;13) is unique to Luke and addressed to the disciples (not the Pharisees, who reappear in v.14). The parable&#8217;s setting is the Palestinian large-estate economy: a wealthy landowner employs an <em>oikonomos</em> (estate manager/steward) who manages the master&#8217;s debtors and accounts. The accusation of &#8220;wasting possessions&#8221; (<em>diaskorpiz&#333;n</em>) uses the same verb as the prodigal son&#8217;s waste (15:13), connecting the two parables.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&#8220;Give an account of your management&#8221; (<em>apodos ton logon t&#275;s oikonomias sou</em>) &#8212; the rendering of accounts was a formal legal procedure; the steward is being dismissed and must account for all his transactions. The finality of &#8220;you cannot be manager any longer&#8221; means his window to act is the period between the accounting order and the final audit. The steward&#8217;s problem is both immediate (loss of employment) and future (no means of support after dismissal).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The steward&#8217;s self-assessment &#8212; &#8220;I&#8217;m not strong enough to dig, I&#8217;m ashamed to beg&#8221; &#8212; reveals class consciousness: manual labor (<em>skapt&#333;</em>, digging) was associated with slaves and the poor; begging was social death for a person of any standing in the Mediterranean world. The steward&#8217;s predicament is that he has a white-collar skill set (accounts, relationships, negotiation) but is losing the position from which those skills were exercised.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&#8220;I know what I&#8217;ll do so that, when I lose my job here, people will welcome me into their homes&#8221; &#8212; the steward&#8217;s plan is to create social obligations among the master&#8217;s debtors by reducing their debts; when he loses his position, these debtors will owe him personal hospitality. The goal is not escape but relational capital &#8212; transforming economic transactions into social bonds. This is the Mediterranean patronage system&#8217;s logic applied deliberately and strategically.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The steward summons each debtor individually &#8212; the private one-on-one transaction ensures no debtor knows what others are being offered. The master&#8217;s debtors are agricultural tenants or merchants who owe the estate produce; their debts are substantial (100 bath-measures of oil, 100 kor of wheat). The steward still has access to the accounts and the legal authority to modify them before his dismissal is finalized; this is the window he exploits.</p>",
    "6": "<p>One hundred bath-measures of oil reduced to fifty &#8212; the <em>batos</em> was approximately 8 gallons; 100 bath was roughly 800 gallons of olive oil, a major agricultural commodity. The reduction of 50% is substantial. Some interpreters identify the removed portion as the steward&#8217;s own commission or interest rate that he was adding to the master&#8217;s bills &#8212; making the reduction not fraud against the master but self-sacrifice of the steward&#8217;s own profit margin. This interpretation makes the master&#8217;s subsequent commendation less scandalous.</p>",
    "7": "<p>One hundred kor of wheat reduced to eighty &#8212; the <em>koros</em> was approximately 10-12 bushels; 100 kor was a very large wheat debt. The 20% reduction is smaller in percentage than the oil reduction (50%) but larger in absolute terms. If the removed portions represent the steward&#8217;s own surcharges, he is buying future hospitality by sacrificing his own income. The parallel structure of the two transactions (bill alteration, quick document-writing) emphasizes the steward&#8217;s shrewd, decisive action under time pressure.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&#8220;The master commended the dishonest manager because he had acted shrewdly&#8221; &#8212; the master&#8217;s commendation is the most difficult element of the parable. The commendation is for <em>phr&#333;nim&#333;s</em> (shrewdly, practically-wisely) acting, not for honesty. &#8220;The people of this world are more shrewd in dealing with their own kind than are the people of the light&#8221; &#8212; the disciples are being challenged to deploy equal prudence and strategic thinking for the kingdom that the world&#8217;s people deploy for their economic interests.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&#8220;Use worldly wealth (<em>mam&#333;na t&#275;s adikias</em>) to gain friends for yourselves&#8221; &#8212; <em>mamōnas</em> is the Aramaic word for wealth/property (not pejorative in itself); &#8220;of unrighteousness&#8221; qualifies it as belonging to the fallen age. The instruction is to use money the way the steward used it: to create relationships and obligations that will outlast the money. &#8220;When it is gone, you will be welcomed into eternal dwellings&#8221; (<em>aionious sk&#275;n&#257;s</em>) &#8212; the eternal equivalent of the steward&#8217;s &#8220;welcome me into their homes&#8221; (v.4).</p>",
    "10": "<p>&#8220;Whoever can be trusted with very little can also be trusted with much&#8221; &#8212; the faithfulness-scales principle moves from the steward&#8217;s situation to a general principle about character: trustworthiness is a consistent character quality that shows itself in small and large contexts alike. The Mishnah (<em>Avot</em> 4:2: &#8220;one mitzvah leads to another mitzvah&#8221;) applies the same principle to obedience; faithfulness in small things is the training ground for trustworthiness in large things.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&#8220;If you have not been trustworthy in handling worldly wealth, who will trust you with true riches?&#8221; &#8212; the contrast between <em>mamōnas</em> (worldly wealth) and &#8220;true riches&#8221; (<em>alēthinon</em>) frames money as a test-case for handling the real thing. In the Jewish wisdom tradition, wisdom and the fear of the Lord are the true riches (Prov 3:14; 8:10&#8211;11; Sir 4:1&#8211;10). Faithfulness in the economy of this age is the prerequisite for participation in the economy of the age to come.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&#8220;Trustworthy with someone else&#8217;s property&#8221; &#8212; worldly wealth is framed as <em>allotrion</em> (another&#8217;s property, belonging to someone else), not truly yours. The steward&#8217;s situation illustrates this: he managed wealth that was not his; his failure was that he wasted it as if it were his own. The disciple who manages worldly wealth faithfully demonstrates the character needed for &#8220;property of your own&#8221; (<em>hymeteran</em>, your own) &#8212; the eschatological inheritance of the kingdom.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&#8220;No one can serve two masters&#8221; &#8212; the slave-owner social structure makes the metaphor concrete: a slave owned by two masters would have divided loyalties in every specific task; the masters&#8217; competing claims would make every decision a conflict. <em>Mam&#333;nas</em> as a quasi-divine power competing with God for ultimate allegiance is the Lukan wealth theology underlying chs. 12, 16, 18&#8211;19; the conclusion is that the disciples must choose their master &#8212; not manage a compromise between two absolute claims.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The Pharisees&#8217; love of money (<em>philargyroi</em>, money-loving) is Luke&#8217;s characterization that connects the teaching of vv.1&#8211;13 to the following controversy. Their sneering (<em>exemuktērizon</em>, turned up their noses, lit. mocked with the nose) echoes Ps 22:7 (the sufferer mocked by those who stick out their lips and shake their heads). Josephus does not particularly associate Pharisees with wealth; Luke&#8217;s characterization may reflect the critique that the Pharisees&#8217; purity and tithing system benefited the wealthy who could afford to maintain it.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&#8220;You are the ones who justify yourselves in the eyes of others, but God knows your hearts&#8221; &#8212; the contrast between outward self-justification (<em>dikaiountes heautous en&#333;pion t&#333;n anthr&#333;p&#333;n</em>) and divine heart-knowledge. &#8220;God knows your hearts&#8221; (<em>kardiogn&#333;st&#275;s</em>) is an explicit divine attribute (Acts 1:24; 15:8 apply it to God and Jesus). &#8220;What people value highly is detestable in God&#8217;s sight&#8221; (<em>bdelygma en&#333;pion tou theou</em>) &#8212; the OT language of idolatry applied to the wealth-prestige system: the love of money is a form of idolatry.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&#8220;The Law and the Prophets were proclaimed until John. Since that time, the good news of the kingdom of God is being proclaimed&#8221; &#8212; Luke&#8217;s clearest statement of the salvation-historical turning point; Acts 13:24&#8211;25 and 19:4 use John as the hinge of the two eras. &#8220;Everyone is forcing their way into it&#8221; (<em>pas eis aut&#275;n biazetai</em>) &#8212; the kingdom is being entered with urgency and force; the passive may be &#8220;everyone is being urged into it&#8221; or the active &#8220;everyone is pressing into it violently.&#8221; Luke&#8217;s context suggests the urgency of the kingdom proclamation: the open door is being pressed through.</p>",
    "17": "<p>&#8220;It is easier for heaven and earth to disappear than for the least stroke of a pen to drop out of the Law&#8221; &#8212; the permanent validity of Torah is asserted immediately after the announcement of a new salvation-historical era. The &#8220;least stroke of a pen&#8221; (the keraia, the smallest mark in a Hebrew letter, equivalent to a serif) echoes Matt 5:18&#8217;s &#8220;not one jot or tittle.&#8221; Luke&#8217;s placement between v.16 (kingdom-era) and v.18 (divorce) suggests that the kingdom does not nullify Torah but fulfills and intensifies it.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The divorce saying &#8212; brief and without exception clause (unlike Matt 5:32&#8217;s &#8220;except for marital unfaithfulness&#8221;) &#8212; is placed between the Torah-permanence saying (v.17) and the Rich Man and Lazarus parable (v.19&#8211;31). The context is the Law&#8217;s application in the kingdom age: Jesus&#8217;s one-flesh teaching (Gen 2:24) makes divorce-and-remarriage equivalent to adultery. The Pharisaic school of Hillel permitted divorce on relatively broad grounds (Deut 24:1, &#8220;something objectionable&#8221;); the school of Shammai permitted it only for sexual immorality; Jesus&#8217;s ruling is stricter than either.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Lazarus at the gate (<em>pyl&#333;n</em>, the formal entrance to a substantial house) &#8212; the only named character in a Jesus parable; the name &#8220;Lazarus&#8221; (<em>El&#8217;azar</em>, God has helped) is a theological irony: the one whose very name declares divine help receives none from the rich man at whose gate he lies. The gate (<em>pylon</em>) in an ancient Mediterranean city was the public face of the household&#8217;s wealth and status; Lazarus&#8217;s placement there makes the rich man&#8217;s failure to help inescapably deliberate.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&#8220;Even the dogs came and licked his sores&#8221; &#8212; dogs (<em>kynaria</em>) in antiquity were not domestic pets but scavengers; they gathered wherever there was food, refuse, or disease. Their licking of Lazarus&#8217;s sores is not comfort but further degradation &#8212; the contact of unclean animals with his wounds. The table-scraps (<em>psichi&#333;n</em>, crumbs) that fall from the rich man&#8217;s table are the minimum of social charity; the contrast with the &#8220;fine food&#8221; of the rich man&#8217;s daily feasting makes the neglect inexcusable. &#8220;No one gave him anything&#8221; echoes 15:16 (the prodigal&#8217;s situation).</p>",
    "22": "<p>&#8220;Angels carried him to Abraham&#8217;s side&#8221; (<em>eis ton kolpon Abraam</em>) &#8212; Abraham&#8217;s bosom/lap was the Jewish term for the blessed state after death; Josephus describes the righteous as resting &#8220;in the bosom of Abraham&#8221; (<em>War</em> 2.155). The angelic escort of the righteous soul to Paradise is found in <em>T. Asher</em> 6:4&#8211;6 and other Second Temple sources. The rich man&#8217;s burial (<em>etaphe</em>) is mentioned in contrast: an elaborately prepared earthly burial vs. an angelic escort to heavenly rest &#8212; the final inversion of their earthly positions.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Hades &#8212; the Greek term for the underworld (translating Hebrew <em>Sheol</em>); in Second Temple Jewish thought, Hades contained both the righteous and wicked in separate sections (4 Ezra 7:85&#8211;87; 1 En. 22:9&#8211;14; Luke 23:43 uses &#8220;paradise&#8221; for the blessed section). The rich man can see Lazarus in the distance &#8212; the reversal is visible: the beggar who lay at the gate, unseen in his need, is now seen in Abraham&#8217;s embrace; the rich man who feasted in visible luxury now suffers in visible torment.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&#8220;Father Abraham, have pity on me&#8221; &#8212; the rich man&#8217;s appeal to Abraham as &#8220;father&#8221; invokes Jewish ethnic identity: John the Baptist had warned that claiming Abraham as father was insufficient (3:8). The request for Lazarus to bring water (a single drop on the tongue) reveals the rich man&#8217;s continued assumption that Lazarus is available for errand-running &#8212; the persistence of the patron-client power structure that characterized his earthly life. He still thinks of Lazarus as below him, a person to be sent.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Abraham&#8217;s reply &#8220;Son, remember&#8221; (<em>teknon, mn&#275;sth&#275;ti</em>) &#8212; the address as &#8220;son&#8221; (<em>teknon</em>) confirms the genetic-covenantal relationship while explaining the reversal. The principle is the Lukan Beatitudes and Woes in concentrated form: you received your good things, Lazarus received bad things; now the positions are reversed. The finality of the eschatological reversal is the counterpart to the Magnificat&#8217;s vision (1:52&#8211;53): what God will do, he has now permanently done.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&#8220;A great chasm has been set in place&#8221; (<em>chasma mega est&#275;riktai</em>) &#8212; the verb <em>st&#275;riz&#333;</em> (to fix firmly, establish permanently) &#8212; the same word used for Jesus &#8220;setting his face&#8221; toward Jerusalem (9:51) and for the Tower of Siloam (13:4). The permanence of the post-mortem state is the parable&#8217;s structural claim: the reversals of the eschaton are fixed and irreversible. This is not systematic afterlife theology but a warning embedded in a parable: the eschatological reversal is real and final.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The second request &#8212; &#8220;send Lazarus to my family&#8221; &#8212; shifts from personal relief to prophetic warning for the five brothers still alive. Having failed to get relief, the rich man asks for a resurrection-appearance to warn his kin. The motivation may be genuine concern for his brothers &#8212; possibly the first moment of care for others he has expressed &#8212; or it may be a continuing use of Lazarus as an instrument. Either way, the request reveals the rich man&#8217;s continued assumption that miraculous intervention is what converts people.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&#8220;Warn them, so that they will not also come to this place of torment&#8221; &#8212; the five brothers represent those still alive who have the same wealth and same blindness as their dead brother. The protective motivation mirrors the OT prophetic concern for the household (Ezek 3:17&#8211;19; 33:7&#8211;9: the watchman must warn). But the mechanism proposed (a resurrection-appearance) is precisely what the rich man thinks will accomplish what Torah and the Prophets have failed to do.</p>",
    "29": "<p>&#8220;They have Moses and the Prophets; let them listen to them&#8221; &#8212; Abraham&#8217;s answer asserts the radical sufficiency of scripture. The Torah and the Prophets contain everything needed to produce the repentance and generosity that would have prevented the rich man&#8217;s situation. Deut 15:7&#8211;11 (open your hand to the poor), Isa 58:6&#8211;7 (share your food with the hungry), Ezek 16:49 (the sin of Sodom: failure to help the poor and needy) &#8212; the scripture is not silent about economic obligation to Lazarus-figures.</p>",
    "30": "<p>&#8220;If someone from the dead goes to them, they will repent&#8221; &#8212; the rich man&#8217;s assumption is that a miraculous sign &#8212; a resurrection-appearance &#8212; would accomplish what scripture has not. This assumption lies behind many requests for signs throughout Luke (11:16,29; 23:8). The assumption is also the Sadducean position in reverse: those who deny resurrection think a resurrection-appearance would be overwhelming proof; the parable&#8217;s answer challenges both the assumption that extraordinary signs convert and the premise that scripture is insufficient.</p>",
    "31": "<p>&#8220;If they do not listen to Moses and the Prophets, they will not be convinced even if someone rises from the dead&#8221; &#8212; the conclusion is a direct Lukan pointer to the resurrection of Jesus: those who rejected the OT witness (the leaders of Israel who knew Moses and the Prophets) were not convinced by the resurrection of Jesus (Acts 2&#8211;5 documents the rejection). The parable&#8217;s final word frames the entire Gospel&#8217;s narrative arc: the resurrection will happen, and some will not believe it because they have already refused to hear what Moses and the Prophets said about it.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'luke')
    merge_comm(existing, DATA)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH14)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH15)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH16)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'luke', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f"Luke mkt-context: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses written.")

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
